## Technical Specifications

Data Models (Schema highlights)
- users
  - id: UUID PK
  - email: string
  - status: string (active | suspended)
  - plan: string (plan name or id)
  - credits: number
  - connectedRepos: array or separate repos table relation
  - lastActive: timestamp
  - isAdmin: boolean
  - createdAt: timestamp
  - updatedAt: timestamp

- connected_repos (or repos)
  - id: UUID PK
  - userId: UUID FK -> users.id
  - repoName: string
  - provider: string
  - connectionStatus: string
  - lastSynced: timestamp

- jobs
  - id: UUID PK
  - type: string
  - status: string
  - attempts: number
  - nextRunAt: timestamp
  - payload: jsonb

- api_keys
  - keyId: UUID PK
  - keyValueHash: string
  - usageCount: number
  - lastUsed: timestamp
  - createdAt: timestamp
  - revokedAt: timestamp (nullable)

- audit_log
  - id: UUID PK
  - adminUserId: UUID FK -> users.id
  - actionType: string
  - targetTable: string
  - targetId: UUID
  - payload: jsonb
  - timestamp: timestamp
  - ipAddress: string

- health_metrics
  - snapshotId: UUID PK
  - timestamp: timestamp
  - queueLength: integer
  - failedJobs: integer
  - throughput: integer
  - apiCalls: integer

- plans
  - id: UUID PK
  - name: string
  - price: numeric
  - credits: integer
  - features: jsonb

API Endpoints (Routes and Methods)
- Admin auth and RBAC
  - POST /admin/auth/verify (token, role) — verify admin privileges
- Users
  - GET /admin/users?search=&plan=&status=&page=&pageSize=
  - POST /admin/users/{id}/credits (delta or set) — adjust credits
  - POST /admin/users/{id}/purge — purge data
  - GET /admin/users/{id}/repos — fetch connected repos
  - POST /admin/users/{id}/suspend / activate
- Health and Jobs
  - GET /admin/health
  - POST /admin/health/retry/{jobId}
  - POST /admin/health/pause
  - POST /admin/health/resume
- API Keys
  - GET /admin/apikeys
  - POST /admin/apikeys/{keyId}/revoke
  - POST /admin/apikeys/{keyId}/rotate
- Audit
  - GET /admin/audit?page=&pageSize=&from=&to=&actionType=
  - POST /admin/audit/export (optional)

Security and Validation
- Authentication: Supabase authentication; Admin endpoints protected by RBAC (isAdmin true) in policies.
- Authorization: Role-based access control; server-side checks mirror client checks; audit log writes immutable.
- Input validation: Use strict server-side validation for all inputs; guard against SQL injection and XSS; validate IDs with UUID checks.
- Data privacy: Purge actions delete user data in compliance; ensure audit entries saved.
- Rate limiting: Apply to admin endpoints to mitigate abuse.

Validation Rules
- All API responses must default to safe structures: const data = Array.isArray(resp?.data) ? resp.data : [].
- When rendering lists, guard with (data ?? []) and render loading skeletons until data resolves.
- Destructuring with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}.
- Use Optional chaining for nested API objects: obj?.property?.nested.

Testing and QA
- Unit tests for each frontend component with null-safety checks.
- Integration tests for admin flows: login as admin, search users, purge a user with audit log generation, retry a failed job, rotate API key, purge data, and view health metrics.
- End-to-end tests for admin authorization: non-admin cannot access admin routes.
- Backend tests validating RBAC policies and data integrity after purge/credit changes.
- Manual UI checks for all design tokens (colors, typography, spacing) across breakpoints.

Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] All admin endpoints are protected by admin RBAC and Supabase RLS policies.
- [ ] Admin UI properly guards against null/undefined when rendering lists and charts (no runtime errors).
- [ ] Admin actions (purge, credit adjust, retry, revoke key) create immutable audit logs with correct metadata.
- [ ] Admin Dashboard reflects system health metrics and usage analytics, with graceful handling of missing data.
- [ ] User management page supports searching, filtering, viewing connected repos, and per-user actions with confirmation flows.
- [ ] Data visualizations adhere to the spec color palette and design system, with accessible controls.
- [ ] All forms have validation and error handling; inputs sanitize and reflect updated state after actions.
- [ ] UI/UX adheres to typography and layout guidelines, with responsive behavior and accessible controls.

---

## UI/UX Guidelines (Design System Applied)

Visual Style
- Color Palette: as provided (teal gradients, pale aqua accents, dark primary text, subtle borders).
- Typography: Inter or Poppins; H1 48–64px, H2 24–32px, body 16px, captions 12–14px.
- Layout: centered hero content with max content width 980–1100px; generous vertical rhythm (48–96px between sections); three-column feature grid on large screens becoming single-column on smaller widths.
- Card Design: 14–18px radius, white surface, light border (#E6E9EE), subtle shadow; hover lift and border darkening.
- Navigation: top white bar, left logo, muted center links, right primary pill CTA; active states with darker text or teal underline.
- Data Visualization: minimalist, flat charts with teal gradient bars, light gridlines (#E6E9EE).
- Interactive Elements: primary, secondary, ghost/outline buttons; focus states with pale teal glow; micro-interactions with 150–220ms transitions.
- Badges/Pills: pale aqua background with teal text for “New” or critical highlights.

Accessibility and Usability
- Keyboard accessible controls; ARIA labels; color contrasts meet AA standards.
- Clear affordances for destructive actions via confirmation modals.
- Progressive disclosure for advanced admin actions; default to safe states.

Development Notes
- Follow the runtime safety rules strictly:
  - Use data ?? [] for Supabase-like results; guard all array operations with Array.isArray checks or (items ?? []) pattern.
  - Initialize all array state with useState<Type[]>([]) and avoid useState() without default for arrays.
  - Validate API responses using Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
  - Use optional chaining for nested data (obj?.prop?.subprop).
  - Destructure with defaults where applicable: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}.

This prompt should be used to guide AI-driven development across frontend, backend, and integration layers, ensuring robust, secure, and scalable Admin Tools & Analytics functionality while upholding the design system and runtime safety constraints. for style.

CRITICAL DESIGN REQUIREMENTS:
- You MUST follow ALL design principles and patterns specified in the Design Reference above
- Do NOT deviate from the design specifications without explicit user permission
- Implement ALL visual design elements (colors, typography, spacing, shadows, animations) as specified
- Follow the layout patterns and component designs exactly as documented
- Ensure all interactions and micro-animations match the reference specifications

CRITICAL TECHNICAL REQUIREMENTS:
- React 18.3.1, React Router 6.30.1
- Tailwind CSS v3 with tailwind.config.js and custom keyframes
- @tailwindcss/typography plugin for rich text content
- Tailwind CSS animations (NOT Motion library or framer-motion)
- Sonner for toasts
- Recharts for data visualization
- Native fetch() with API utilities in src/lib/api.ts
- Design system with CSS custom properties
- Use RGB color values for theming
- When Supabase is configured: use Edge Functions for LLM and server-only logic; never expose API keys in the client


=== EDGE FUNCTIONS & DATABASE MIGRATIONS (MANDATORY) ===

Even without a Supabase project connected, you MUST create the correct files when the task requires them:

EDGE FUNCTIONS - create supabase/functions/<function-name>/index.ts for:
- LLM/AI features (chat, completions, embeddings, vector search)
- Third-party API integrations (Stripe, SendGrid, Twilio, OpenAI, Anthropic, etc.)
- Incoming webhooks from external services
- Any server-only logic or logic that must not expose secrets to the client
- Any prompt that says "create edge function" or "add edge function"
File location: supabase/functions/<function-name>/index.ts
Import pattern: import { serve } from "https://deno.land/std@0.168.0/http/server.ts";
Never expose API keys or secrets in client-side code.

DATABASE MIGRATIONS - create supabase/migrations/<YYYYMMDDHHmmss>_<description>.sql for:
- Every new database table, view, or enum mentioned in the task
- Every schema change (ALTER TABLE, new index, new policy, etc.)
- Any prompt that says "create migration" or describes a data model
Make migrations idempotent (IF NOT EXISTS / CREATE OR REPLACE). Include RLS policies.
Do NOT run "supabase db push" or execute SQL directly — only create the .sql files.

MANDATORY CHECKLIST - Before finishing, verify:
- [ ] Migration SQL file(s) created for every database table/schema change mentioned
- [ ] Edge Function file(s) created for every server-side/secrets feature mentioned
- [ ] TypeScript types created for every new database table

=== TASK ===
# Admin Tools & Analytics

## Overview
Develop a comprehensive Admin Tools & Analytics suite for RepoMarket that enables secure admin-only monitoring, user management, system health insight, and operational controls. This includes dashboards and pages to observe analytics derived from Supabase metrics/logs, manage users (search, connect repos, purge data, adjust plans/credits), and execute admin operations such as queue/job retries and API key usage auditing. All endpoints and UI must enforce RBAC with Supabase policies, log admin actions immutably, and guard against null/undefined values in runtime code. The project should remain lean, with Supabase handling authentication, database, and storage, and integrations with GitHub, Anthropic, and Perplexity as described.

Associated Pages:
- page_admin_017
- page_admin_018

Target stack notes:
- Frontend: React (with hooks), TypeScript, likely Next.js or a similar framework. Use useState/useEffect patterns with robust null checks.
- Backend: Supabase (Postgres) for auth, policies, and storage; REST/Edge API routes or RPCs for admin operations.
- Integrations: GitHub for repo ingestion, Anthropic for repository context interpretation, Perplexity for external market data gathering.
- Data: Structured audit log of admin actions; metrics/logs derived from Supabase.

---

## Components to Build
1. Admin Dashboard (Internal Admin Console)
   - Overview widgets: system health (uptime, queue length, error rate), usage metrics (API calls, active users, plan distributions), recent admin actions.
   - Charts: compact, minimalistic charts with teal gradients (#2FD7BC → #14B9A0) and neutral axes (#D1D5DB).
   - Modals: confirm destructive actions (purge user data, force retry, disable API keys).
   - Cards: user management snippets, top API clients, recent audits.

2. Admin — User Management (page_admin_017)
   - Search and filter users (by email, id, plan, status, last active).
   - View connected repos per user; purge user data; adjust plan/credits.
   - Inline actions: edit user details, add credits, suspend/reactivate, assign roles.
   - Purge data flow: multi-step confirm with audit trail.
   - Data display: paginated table with robust guards for missing fields.

3. Admin Tools & Analytics (Core Admin Features)
   - Health monitoring: queue status, job retries, failed job counts, worker throughput.
   - Operational controls: queue/job retry, manual re-run triggers, pause/resume queues.
   - API keys usage: view, filter by key, usage counts, revoke keys, rotate keys.
   - Audit log: immutable trail of admin actions with timestamp, admin user, target entity, action type, and payload diff.

4. Admin Data Visualization Components
   - Compact charts and micro-visuals for metrics: bar charts, line trends, donut gauges for quotas.
   - Data source integration: consume from Supabase metrics/logs, with guards to handle null results.

5. Reusable UI Primitives (per design system)
   - Cards, grids, forms, inputs, selects, toggles, buttons (primary/secondary/ghost/teal accents).
   - Badges/pills (New, Warning, Inactive) with pale aqua backgrounds and teal text.
   - Tables with stable headers, sortable columns, and adjustable page sizes.
   - Confirmation modals and toast notifications for admin actions.

